The Lady⁠
Credit: Elizaveta Loseva @ellos3d⁠
⁠
"My latest personal project.⁠
The main goal of this one was to learn Unreal Engine. As well as to try my hand at both more complex game-ready hairstyles and more mature women's faces.⁠
⁠
The main inspiration was a photo of actress Kristin Scott Thomas portraying Lady Ternan. In this photo, her posture and attitude were a perfect interpretation of the Lady of that time. I liked the photo so much, and the decision to create the model was almost instant. 😊⁠
I hope you'll like it.⁠
⁠
Polycount: 80k tris whole bust, 45k tris only hair mesh/cards⁠
Tafira originally made the image used as a base for the shawl flower pattern."⁠
⁠
Credit Link: https://www.artstation.com/artwork/ZG4aO1 (ArtStation)⁠

Nowhere [UE5]⁠
Credit: Anastasia Mist⁠
⁠
"Hello everyone!⁠
I present to you my latest project. I started this to create a complex atmospheric scene on my own from the ground up. And, since Unreal Engine 5 has become available to the public, I don't miss the opportunity to explore this amazing new version.⁠
⁠
I made all the materials, trims, and models. All of them are game-ready and optimized. Some materials include the vertex paint option to add variability. The Megascans library was used for decals and foliage. And as for the framed paintings, I take the works of a wonderful artist — John William Waterhouse."⁠

node.text:
Extreme E - Odyssey 21 (2021)⁠
Credit: Rosa van Wouwe⁠
⁠
"Very happy to finally show off this project! Aurora Media Worldwide asked us to create an explainer video about the Odyssey 21 - a fully electric SUV created by Spark Racing Technology - for the new big racing series: Extreme-E! Extreme-E is all about racing in remote locations, fully electric SUVs, raising awareness for climate change and gender equality.⁠
⁠
The video is rendered completely in Unreal Engine 4.26 and has ray-traced ambient occlusion, global illumination, and reflections. The car model was built from a CAD file of which we re-modeled or re-topologized most parts. For the tires, I baked down the high poly model to a normal map. The bodywork is remodeled and uv'ed. A mask of the livery was created in Substance Painter and used in the engine to create the right colors and material properties in those areas. For some parts of the car, we used Quad Remesher to get a decent mesh to use in the engine.⁠
⁠
The environment consists of mostly Quixel Megascans assets (Iceland environment) and is hand-placed by Jordy and me. For the terrain, I created a landscape material that blends between 3 different materials. The mountains in the back of the scene are from a Brushify pack (can be found on the UE4 Marketplace).⁠
For the effect where the car's body is taken off, I created a material with a couple of parameters that are part of a material parameter collection. I could control and animate the parameters in the level sequencer to get the timing right.⁠
⁠
Jordy de Lat does the camera work, compositing, and lighting.⁠
Check out what else he worked on right here: (https://www.artstation.com/cloudjor)⁠
⁠
I had a lot of help with modeling and re-topologizing from Thomas Lazarom: (https://www.artstation.com/thompsongast)⁠
⁠
And some of the retop work was done by Kevin de Ligt:⁠
(https://www.artstation.com/kevindeligt)"⁠
⁠
⁠
Credit Link: https://www.artstation.com/artwork/5XzKaw (ArtStation)⁠

node.text:
Artstation Challenge: Grand Space Opera - Light Age⁠
Credit: Alex Karabardin⁠
⁠
"It's been 6 months since Artstation Challenge started, and it's finally ready. From the beginning, I understood that I wanted to do more than I could handle in two months, so I made two versions: one for the AS challenge and a final one, which I'm glad to publish here.⁠
The original idea was taken from David VDB, which was made for the first part of the challenge.⁠
(https://www.artstation.com/contests/grand-space-opera-light-age/challenges/93/submissions/57664)⁠
⁠
However, I desired to expand this idea to a "Subnautica-style" crash site, work more with hard-surface forms. Our player is assumed to explore nature around the landing zone on a distant planet and find out if this planet is interesting for our civilization.⁠
The terrain was generated in Houdini and then recreated in Unreal Engine with a Houdini Digital Asset. Then I used a pretty standard pipeline with some variations. The materials are compilations of solutions from all around the Internet.⁠
I want to thank everyone who gave me feedback during this time, especially my mentor Sergey Panin. I really appreciate his patience, seriously. 6 months, guys.⁠
(https://www.artstation.com/leoluch)⁠
⁠
To see more of the process, feel free to visit my Artstation Challenge page. (https://www.artstation.com/contests/grand-space-opera-light-age/challenges/97/submissions/60930)⁠
⁠
And of course, I'm looking forward to knowing what you think about the mood and the work in general!"⁠
⁠

node.text:
The Water Temple - Leartes Studios & Dekogon "Post-Apocalyptic" Real-Time Environment Challenge⁠
Credit: Rodrigo Castro @rodrigocascas⁠
⁠
"This is my entry for the Leartes Studios & Dekogon "Post-Apocalyptic" Real-Time Environment Challenge⁠
For the challenge, I’ve chosen Eddie Mendoza’s concept art: The Water Temple. (https://www.artstation.com/artwork/58e6nE) ⁠
⁠
I used Unreal engine 4.26 Dynamic Lighting (not Ray Tracing), GTX 1070.⁠
I wanted to explore new techniques I didn't know about optimization on materials and textures; Learning the workflow of trim sheets and masking with ORM textures using the channels for Curvature, Dirt, and Damage details.⁠
I did everything in the scene except the water, the fire, and the particles.⁠
⁠
This was one of the biggest challenges I have participated in until now. Normally I do big personal projects but never as big and dedicated as this one.⁠
I really learned a lot working on this. I am thrilled with the result.⁠
⁠
You can see more of my workflow in the 4 Blogs I posted on the process."⁠
⁠
Credit Link: https://www.artstation.com/artwork/8e3gmG (ArtStation)⁠

Credit: Anthony German Ballinas⁠
